Using the Limulus amoebocyte lyase assay, we firstly confirmed that recombinant PspA solution was free of detectable LPS (<0.1 EU/ml). To generate a profile of cytokine and chemokine that may be regulated by PspA, the effect of PspA on inflammatory cytokine IL-6, chemokines including CXCL8, CCL2, CCL4, and CCL5 was examined. Human monocytes (5 × 105 cells) were stimulated with indicated concentrations of PspA for indicated times (Fig. 1
). Under the experimental conditions used in these experiments, cell viability was consistently > 90%, indicating that the recombinant PspA preparations used did not induce significant death of monocytes. We found that PspA significantly induced IL-6 (A), CXCL8 (B), CCL2 (C), CCL5 (D) and CCL4 (E) secretion in comparison with control at the 12-hour and 24-hour time points, and the secretion of these mediators induced by PspA could be enhanced dose-dependently (50–1000 ng/ml) at 12 and 24 h. In addition, the maximal responses occurred at 24 h of PspA stimulation for all of these mediators. However, the secretion of other inflammatory cytokines TNF-α, IL-1β and chemokine CCL3 could not be induced by PspA from human monocytes (Fig. 2
). Besides, we found that this PspA activation could not enhance the capacity of human monocytes to internalize and clear TIGR4 pneumococcus in a direct functional test in vitro (data not shown).

Regarding the signal transduction mechanisms, we took advantage of a rapid and quantitative method. Using intracellular fluorescence staining by flow cytometry, we measured the contents of phosphorylated ERK, JNK, p38MAPK and IκB-α in permeabilized monocytes. The representative flow cytometry histograms in Fig. 6
illustrated that the untreated human monocytes had a basal activity of ERK, JNK, p38 MAPK and IκB-α. However, human monocytes treated with PspA for 15 min were shown to significantly up-regulate expressions of phosphorylated ERK, JNK, p38 MAPK and IκB-α. The phosphorylation of ERK, JNK, p38 MAPK and IκB-α was highly reproducibly detectable in human monocytes on 15 min, stimulation with PspA by means of Western blot (Fig. 7
). These data further confirmed the results from inhibitor assays described above.
